Drunk on corruption
My friend Boris was leaving my place, drunk.
I therefore suggested that he should not drive.
He asked me why.
"I have noticed that you have been drinking," I said, "are you not afraid of the police?"
Boris replied, "no, I have a document featuring Benjamin Franklin's portrait, and it's always useful."
He showed me his driver's license with the $100 bill slipped beside it.
Of course, I knew that the police took bribes, but I was worried that Boris would meet a policeman who wasn't corrupted.
"Impossible," declared Boris, "to join the police unit responsible for traffic control, you have to buy your boss's silence."
If you don't take bribes, how can you buy your boss's silence?
Half of the drivers in Moscow use illegally purchased driving licenses.
The idiocy of those who try to do things by the book gets bogged down in administrative hassle.
Here is the translation of the sentence from French to English:  "Paying 100 dollars allows you to drive in town without brakes!"
Corruption and fund embezzlement have always existed in Russia, both before Lenin's October Revolution and after.
But never at the record levels we see today.
Everyone accepts bribes everywhere and for anything.
According to Boris, the only ones who don't accept it are those to whom it is not offered.
Corruption thrives in most institutions, and the fight against corruption always ends in catastrophe or abandonment.
The police, the prosecutors, the customs officers, and even the Kremlin: nobody is immune anywhere.
Recently, I was visiting a village of dachas in one of the most beautiful suburbs of Moscow.
It was a luxuriously appointed place but similar to a gulag with its high-security fences and guards.
Examining the pretentious houses decorated with such poor taste, I wondered who owned them and heard an answer that one of them belonged to an alderman of Moscow, another to a famous singer, and yet another to the son of the prosecutor of Moscow.
But the most attractive property belonged to a modest tax official.
Translating the given French sentence to English:  "Corruption now represents a greater threat to Russia than the Chechen war."
In fact, the Chechen war would not have lasted as long if it had not been led by corrupt generals, officers, officials, and police who sell arms and provisions to the rebels.
Recently, Russian television showed a bus shuttling between Grozny and Moscow, the same bus that transported the 120 kilograms of explosives used in the theater siege at Dubrovka, where so many victims perished during the assault aimed at freeing the hostages.
A bus passenger covered the explosives with a wet acid-soaked cloth to prevent customs dogs from detecting them.
A well-useless precaution.
No one controls the buses today.
The driver, who didn't know what he was transporting, said that he was stopped 50 times along his route, and for the same reason each time.
A policeman came up to him and asked, "Do you know what the price is?" and the driver replied, "Of course, I know it," paying the bribe before getting back in his vehicle.
Without a bribe, the bus would have been delayed for hours at each stop, potentially days for the entire journey.
The war in Chechnya continues without end not only because Chechen rebels have allies in Al-Qaeda and all "international terrorism," but also because Russian corruption is their ally.
The police, the army, civilians who accept bribes and thieves, who first tax or simply steal from Chechen civilians, sell weapons and explosives to terrorists, provide minefield maps, and supply rebels with fake documents.
In May of this year, during the Kaspiisk explosions, the terrorists used weapons purchased from Russian army officers.
The rebels have modern weapons.
Where do they come from?
In the mountains where the rebels hide, there are no gun shops.
But the 80,000 Russian soldiers who are fighting the rebels have their own stockpiles of ammunition, from which the weapons are stolen and sold.
And not just weapons: some young officers sell their own men into slavery.
The Russian corruption has reached catastrophic levels, and yet no struggle has been launched against this scourge.
To punish corruption more severely?
This would only increase the prices of corruption.
The harder the punishment, the more one will have to pay to avoid it.
No official wants to fight corruption because they are corrupt themselves.
Thus, those referred to as "ordinary people" consider this phenomenon with benevolence.
They say of their mayor, "yes of course he's stealing, but look at all he's done for the city!"
Ordinary people also do not like honest workers.
Why?
A train ticket costs 100 rubles, but by paying a small bribe, one can travel for 50 rubles.
The traveler and the controller both benefit from this system.
An honest old grandmother once told me that she had bought a ticket and tried to board the train.
The controller had stopped her by telling her that passengers with a ticket were not admitted on the train!
For millions of Russians, corruption is a normal way of life.
If you don't want your son to be called up for military service, buy a conscription clerk who will remove your son's name from the list or bribe a doctor to declare your son unfit for military service.
You can enter any faculty for a certain price, regardless of your references and diplomas.
You can drive drunk, speed excessively, run red lights, as long as Ben Franklin is there to bail you out of trouble with the police.
Pierre the Great's minister Alexander Menchikov had understood the impossibility of winning the fight against corruption.
When Tsar Peter, disgusted by the corruption in Russia, decided to hang his corrupt officials, Menshikov replied: "Your Majesty, you risk losing all your subjects."
In the centuries since, the situation has worsened.
Translating the given French sentence into English:  "Removing corruption could leave the state without citizens, but if we do not stop the advance of corruption, citizens will soon be left without a state."
